Preamble

The GNU Affero General Public License is a free, copyleft license for
software and other kinds of works, specifically designed to ensure
cooperation with the community in the case of network server software.

The licenses for most software and other practical works are designed
to take away your freedom to share and change the works.  By contrast,
our General Public Licenses are intended to guarantee your freedom to
distribute copies and modified versions of the works, to ensure that
the work remains free software for all its users.

When we speak of free software, we are referring to freedom, not
price.  Our General Public Licenses are designed to make sure that you
have the freedom to distribute copies of free software (and charge for
them if you wish), that you receive source code or can get it if you
want it, that you can change the software or use pieces of it in new
free programs, and that you know you can do these things.

Developers that use our license protect your rights with two steps:

1. assert copyright on the software, and
2. offer you this License giving you legal permission to copy, modify
   and/or distribute the software.

An "interactive user interface" displays "Appropriate Legal Notices"
to the extent that it includes a convenient and prominently visible
feature that (1) displays an appropriate copyright notice, and (2)
states that there is no warranty for the work (unless warranty is
explicitly provided), and (3) states that users may redistribute the
work under these conditions, and (4) gives prominent notice that the
work is licensed under this License and how to view a copy of this
License.  If the Program has interactive user interfaces, each must
display Appropriate Legal Notices; however, if the Program has
noninteractive interfaces, the Program may display Appropriate Legal
Notices in the documentation and/or other materials provided along with
the Program.

